question_title: Discrete Mathmatics Help Needed? [SEP] question_content: Describe an algorithm that locates the last occurence of the smallest element in a finite list of integers, where the integers in the list are not necessarily distinct.

What the hell do they mean by "not necessarily distinct"? [SEP] best_answer: The list may contain more than once the same number.
these are all valid lists:
2 1 3 5 9
1 1 1
-5 0 -5 0 -5 1 5

The algorithm will be O(n) (you have to examine every element at least once and once is enough).
c code would be something like this

int *find_last_min(int *list, int length)
{
  int i, *min = list; /* assuming the list is not empty */
  for(i = 1; i < length; ++i)
    if(*min >= list[i])
      min = list + i;
  return min;
}
